    <text id="R12745680T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union General Darius Couch writes from Chambersburg to General William F. Smith
                    regarding plans and movements after the battle of Gettysburg.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Brig.-Gen. Smith:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1863-07-13">July 13, 1863.</date>
                        <name type="place">Chambersburg,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Your note, informing me that you were to move on, and join your forces to Meade,
                    is received.</p>
                <p>If you return to me, there will be enough for us all to do.</p>
                <p>The batteries will not be of much use to Meade, I am fearful, particularly E.
                    Spencer Miller's. Will you leave the transportation or return it?</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully,</salute>
                    <signed>D. N. COUCH,<lb/> Maj.-Gen.</signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">P. S.--It may be that Meade will want you to command the
                        corps. I should like to have you with me if there is to be any fighting done
                        by us, but my opinion is that Gen. Meade should give you a corps. In that
                        case, I would feel that it was all right, and that it was for the best.</seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
